---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
const title = "Land vs improved property: financing differences and gotchas";
const description = "Buying land and buying a home look similar on paper. The financing works completely differently.";
---
<BaseLayout title={`${title} | BRIK`} description={description}>
  <section style="padding:28px 0 10px">
    <h2 style="font-size:30px;margin:0 0 10px;letter-spacing:-.4px">{title}</h2>
    <p style="margin:0 0 18px;color:var(--muted);max-width:82ch">{description}</p>
    <div class="card">
      <h3 style="margin:0 0 8px">Scenario</h3>
      <p style="margin:0;color:var(--muted);font-size:13px;line-height:1.7">
        Kevin wants to buy a wooded lot for $68,000 to build a home in five years. He assumes he can get a mortgage similar to a home purchase. What he discovers is that land loans are a completely different product — higher down payments, higher rates, shorter terms, and far fewer lenders willing to make them. Understanding the difference before shopping saves significant time and frustration.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div style="display:grid;gap:14px;grid-template-columns:repeat(12,1fr);margin-top:14px">
      <div class="card" style="grid-column:span 6">
        <h3 style="margin:0 0 8px">Land loan characteristics</h3>
        <ul style="margin:0;padding-left:18px;color:var(--muted);font-size:13px;line-height:1.7">
          <li>Down payment: typically 20-50% required</li>
          <li>Interest rates: 1-3% higher than home mortgages</li>
          <li>Shorter terms: often 10-15 years vs 30</li>
          <li>Fewer lenders: community banks and credit unions most common</li>
          <li>Raw land vs improved lot — improved lots (utilities in place) are easier to finance</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="card" style="grid-column:span 6">
        <h3 style="margin:0 0 8px">Home/improved property financing</h3>
        <ul style="margin:0;padding-left:18px;color:var(--muted);font-size:13px;line-height:1.7">
          <li>3-20% down payment options widely available</li>
          <li>30-year fixed standard product</li>
          <li>Broad lender market — banks, credit unions, brokers</li>
          <li>Government-backed options (FHA, VA, USDA) available</li>
          <li>Collateral is clear — the structure plus land</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="card" style="margin-top:14px">
      <h3 style="margin:0 0 8px">Things to consider</h3>
      <ul style="margin:0;padding-left:18px;color:var(--muted);font-size:13px;line-height:1.7">
        <li>Is the lot already served by utilities — water, sewer, electric? This dramatically affects financing options.</li>
        <li>What is the timeline to build — lenders get nervous about land held speculatively for years.</li>
        <li>Could you buy the land and immediately contract for construction — converting to a construction-to-perm loan?</li>
        <li>Have you spoken to local community banks — they understand local land markets better than national lenders.</li>
        <li>What is the zoning and are permits obtainable for your intended use — verify before financing.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="card" style="margin-top:14px;background:rgba(255,255,255,.03)">
      <h3 style="margin:0 0 8px">BRIK takeaway</h3>
      <p style="margin:0;color:var(--muted);font-size:13px;line-height:1.7">
        Land financing is harder, more expensive, and less standardized than home financing. Go in knowing that — and work with lenders who specialize in it. The better your lot (utilities in, permits obtainable, clear zoning), the better your financing options will be.
      </p>
      <div style="display:flex;gap:10px;flex-wrap:wrap;margin-top:12px">
        <a class="pill" href="/case-studies">Back to Case Studies</a>
        <a class="pill primary" href="/intake">Submit Intake</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>